<subSubSection id="4C236F67192A079A7B5CE393C713B608" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E02ED67C1A73620A41F643C6941099FB" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="073C81A981A414E9AF727AC66A01C07E" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
Medium sized (7.5-11.6 mm), dark brown species with characteristic large silver microtrichose fasciae on terga 2-4 in males (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="61253580B86346F9E98A2A668B3641EC" captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Body parts, dorsal view. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, male B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, female C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, male D Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, female E Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, male F Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, female. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377384" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">23C</figureCitation>
), and silver michrotrichose ornamentation on scutum in both sexes (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0C569720CC44B96DCBFA193A1DACE631" captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Body parts, dorsal view. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, male B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, female C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, male D Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, female E Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, male F Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, female. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377384" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">23A, B</figureCitation>
); basoflagellomere with rounded apex, 1.6-1.8 times longer than wide in male (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C8C50857B74405C9719861FB46AC24D6" captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., antenna, lateral view. A outer side, male B inner side, male outer side, female. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377394" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">33A, B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="506A86A9F04D325EA141706214293B2E" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="description">
<paragraph id="CFFF9A7BCE13FAE7BACA39DAD8D1CC3A" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="47F917C785C4991031B0D88392FD9031" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis id="E2FB6E0D7665CEE3FC482F7211DCB3BD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Male.</emphasis>
Head. Antennae black to dark brown; basoflagellomere rounded, 1.6-1.8 times as long as wide, and ca. 2.3 times as long as pedicel; large fossette dorsomedial and dorsolateral; arista brown and thickened at basal one third, covered with dense microtrichia, ca. 1.8 times as long as basoflagellomere (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FC35897C00E173579F9F8730CF8EA963" captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., antenna, lateral view. A outer side, male B inner side, male outer side, female. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377394" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">33A, B</figureCitation>
); face and frons black with gray microtrichia, face covered with dense whitish gray, and frons with yellowish gray pile; oral margin shiny with microtrichose lateral areas; lunule shiny black, bare; vertex covered with gray microtrichia; vertex isosceles, with long, pale whitish yellow pile mixed with black pile on the ocellar triangle; ocellar triangle equilateral; eyes covered with dense pile; occiput with gray-yellow pile, covered with a dense, gray microtrichia; eye contiguity 8-12 facets long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A56FD37F640EC792A95221CAE22059AC" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
Thorax. Scutum and scutellum black with bronze luster, covered with dense, erect, yellow pile; scutum with conspicuous silver microtrichose ornamentation (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F9BBB51BF33B69927A009E0EF87AD0F0" captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Body parts, dorsal view. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, male B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, female C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, male D Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, female E Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, male F Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, female. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377384" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">23A</figureCitation>
); posterodorsal part of anterior anepisternum, posterior anepisternum (except anteroventral angle), anterior anepimeron, dorsomedial anepimeron, and posterodorsal and anteroventral parts of katepisternum with long, pale yellow pile and grayish microtrichia; wings entirely covered with microtrichia; wing veins brown; calypteres and halteres pale yellow; legs mostly black, except yellowish tip of femora, basal and apical part of tibiae and brown tarsi ventrally; pile on legs pale yellow; metafemur moderately incrassate, ca. four times longer than wide; pile on metafemur long, and ca. half to two thirds of width of metafemur.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6F0219D8850BCF453C35A1C013C6C3EE" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
Abdomen. Tapering, 1.2 times longer than mesonotum; terga dark, with broad silver microtrichose fasciae; tergum 2 with pale orange lateral maculae; pile on terga all yellow (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A5E7D62527A5D357C4DAAAD490E88688" captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Body parts, dorsal view. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, male B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, female C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, male D Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, female E Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, male F Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, female. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377384" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">23C</figureCitation>
); sterna dark brown, covered with long whitish yellow pile.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ECC68069FE92032AE391181220F55A51" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
Male genitalia. Apical part of anterior surstyle lobe rhomboid shape, approximately as long as wide, covered with dense, short pile (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C7B4402CADB90BC85A98719882D44CC1" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="F34" captionText="Figure 34. Male genitalia. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, lateral view B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, ventral view C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., hypandrium, lateral view. Abbreviations: al-anterior surstyle lobe, bp-basolateral protrusion, l-lingula. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure34" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377395" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">34A</figureCitation>
: al); posterior surstyle lobe oval with basolateral protrusion (lateral hump) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="54CA5316DC60D9CF4EF6BA2B2B743742" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="F34" captionText="Figure 34. Male genitalia. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, lateral view B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, ventral view C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., hypandrium, lateral view. Abbreviations: al-anterior surstyle lobe, bp-basolateral protrusion, l-lingula. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure34" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377395" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">34A, B</figureCitation>
: bp); hypandrium sickle-shaped, without lateral projections; lingula (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="51348BB12A22BE8883321A558D41D561" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="F34" captionText="Figure 34. Male genitalia. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, lateral view B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, ventral view C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., hypandrium, lateral view. Abbreviations: al-anterior surstyle lobe, bp-basolateral protrusion, l-lingula. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure34" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377395" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">34C</figureCitation>
: l).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D8B4DA16673832CC17CD86AB5ABB4FE3" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis id="B69E030E00919E54DE261AC5F3690D84" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Female.</emphasis>
Similar to the male except for normal sexual dimorphism and for the following characteristics: basoflagellomere ca. 1.8 times longer than wide, fossette dorsolateral (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="447F063F5790E09083A4C2C3257B148E" captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., antenna, lateral view. A outer side, male B inner side, male outer side, female. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377394" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">33C</figureCitation>
); frons with microtrichose vittae along eye margins; frons covered with mostly gray-yellow pile mixed with black ones; ocellar triangle covered with black pile; ventral margin of metafemur with sparse pilosity, only individual pile longer; lateral side of terga, anterior two third of tergum 2 and all tergum 5 with whitish pile; terga 2-4 with short adpressed black pile medially; microtrichose fasciae on terga 3 and 4 narrower (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5FEE58652C6B3641FC3F756D91DFCAB1" captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Body parts, dorsal view. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, male B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, female C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, male D Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, female E Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, male F Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, female. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377384" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">23D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F63F02D2597F7D4E9CBBB1404B9A6AAE" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0214ED8ADD27C6A1463B26FABEA519C7" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Etymology.</paragraph>
